On January 20, 2025, at 1309 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Laredo, TX regarding the release of Reze-Meric 9772. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 1.0 ounce of Reze-Meric 9772 (UN1866, 3, II) from (2) 231-gallon poly totes onto the (2) totes. The release was reportedly due loose caps, impacting multiple areas on top of the leaked totes. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The release was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. Contractors tightened the caps on all totes of product and no totes were found to be damaged. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (1) 5-gallon DF, which was then taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

column169: Packaging failure

When performing a facility inspection it was noticed that a dropped trailer had liquid dripping from it around 1530 ct. They the thorough down absorbent to prevent any spread of the material and to begin absorbing it. The facility has a emergency response team located on site and they began the process of cleaning it up. The trailer was unloaded and 3 drum appeared to be swell up and the material was being pushed out of the bungs. The material consisted of mostly water and the drums had frozen causing the expansion. The team released the pressure and placed them into salvage drums. The rest of the material was then cleaned up and disposed of in the appropriate manner. The clean up was completed by 1730 ct. approximately 1 gallon was released.
column170: The facility will perform more inspections on during extreme weather such as cold and heat to monitor any changes with loads that are on site.

This customer has a process in place where we scan multiple items on the trailer and customer set up before a lock code is given to unlock the fill line to be able to deliver.  If that process isn't followed the driver is to call in and go through some manual verifications.  That didn't happen and the unload should not have happened.  Additionally a customer rep unlocked the fill line for him further bypassing protocols and they knew there was too much product for the tank to hold and that it would be a partial unload.  The rep was going to tell him when to shut down.  Ultimately that communication didn't happen and 3-4 gallons overflowed the tank down the sides and into the containment area.  The rep rinsed down the sides of the tank into the containment drain.
column170: The driver was put on a performance improvement plan.  The customer rep also received follow up guidance for not following his company protocols.

column169: When unloading freight from trailer forklift operator was carrying the tote on the forkblades of the forklift. As the forklift was transitioning from the trailer to the dock over the dock plate the IBC started to wobble on the forkblades. The forklift operator tried to move forward back on to the trailer and when doing so the IBC fell over causing the lid to partially rupture contributing to the unintentional release. Defensive actions were immediately taken to contain the spilled material and an outside spill response company was dispatched to aid in mitigating and cleaning up the spilled material. The spilled material was cleaned up by an outside company and placed into multiple recovery containers for disposal.
column170: Forklift operators need to be careful when removing totes of this size from trailer to prevent these types of unintentional releases.

RESPONDER RECEIVED NOTIFICATION OF HAZMAT SPILL AT PENN 4 SPLIT 0530AM PST. HAZMAT RESPONDEDER DAWNED APPROPRIATE GEAR AND RESPONDED. INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE REVEALED HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS WITH CORROSIVE DESIGNATION. PACKAGE OBSERVED WET ON TOP AND BOTTOM OF PACKAGING BOX. HAZMAT NOT SEEPING OUT OF SHIPPING CONTAINER. REMOVED HAZMAT FROM AREA NO SPILLAGE SEEN IN AREA. TRANSPORTED TO DMP FOR PROCESSING. OPENED PACKAGE AND OBSERVED CRACKED LID ON A 1 GALLON JUG. TESTED SOLUTION WITH A PH OF 11 PER COLOR CODED CHART. NEUTRALIZED HAZMAT USING SODIUM BICARBONATE IN ITS OWN PLASTIC CONTAINER. RETESTED SOLUTION 2 TIMES TO VERIFY A PH OF 6. USED A SPILL TRAY LINED WITH PLASTIC BAG AND ZEB ZORBENT AND WOODEN MIXING STICK TO SOLIDIFY SOLUTION. ONCE SOLIDIFIED PUT INITIAL PLASTIC BAG WITH SOLIDIFIED SOLUTION, GLOVES, STIRRING STICK, CARDBOARD PACKAGING, GLOVESS, AND PLASTIC JUG IN GREEN HAZMAT BAG. GOOSE NECKED BAG TAPED AND BEGAN HAZMAT PROCESSING.

XPO Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a two metal totes containing hazardous product, Unisol Liquid Red BK 50. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 0.5-gallon release from two metal totes that impacted 1’x1’ areas on tops and sides of the totes, the wooden trailer floor, and the concrete dock floor. One of the totes had a loose bung cap that was mis-threaded, and the other tote had a loose lid that was easily tightened. The contractor used simple green to clean-up the release and performed slosh tests on the totes. One 55-gallon DM of waste was generated containing impacted rags, floor debris, and PPE. The totes will ship onto the consignee. XPO will manage all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: On January 22, 2025 while conducting a site walk at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Henderson, CO an employee noticed free liquid around the bung of a drum that was loaded onto a trailer for outbound shipment. Approximately 3 ounces of UN3264 Waste Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic, n.o.s. (nitric acid, sulfuric acid), 8, II, RQ (D002) released from the top bung of a drum (1H1) due to liquid expansion during freezing weather conditions. The container was removed from the trailer and was set aside to be overpacked. The impacted area was cleaned by Veolia personnel. No employee exposure or injury was reported.
column170: Veolia's trailer shipments are parked on a pad outside. Due to the freezing temperatures in Colorado during the winter months it is impossible to keep the drums from freezing at times of extreme cold. Veolia will continue daily site walks and will pay close attention to hazmat containers being stored outside during freezing weather to monitor for any leaks and container integrity prior to releasing the shipment for transportation over public roadways.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XWK experienced an over the road release of UN2693 VOxOUT 70C from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 60-gallons of product released to a 20’ x 3’ area of the trailer floor and a 30’ x 3’ area of the asphalt road below. The tote was damaged due to not being strapped down which caused it to load shift into the trailer wall. The material left in the damaged tote was transferred into a new one for shipment on. The impacted areas were then cleaned with absorbents and degreaser. All the impacted snow, absorbents, and debris were containerized into (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The damaged tote was cut up and placed into a cubic yard box. The waste was removed from the site for disposal.
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf
attachment Name:Hazmat- Damaged Haz Mat Package Disposition 04302024.pdf

Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 56ft-by-6ft area of the trailer floor and the dock floor and estimated that seventy-five (75) gallons of material was released due to a forklift puncturing one (1) 55-gallon metal drum of Hi-Temp 1200 causing it to knock over into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum of PBTCA damaging it. Before Clean Harbors’ arrival, Dayton Freight personnel had placed both damaged drums into two (2) 85-gallon overpacks. Clean Harbors personnel deployed the neutralizer sodium bicarbonate and granular absorbents to the impacted area. They used a pH strip to test the paint inside the metal drum which resulted in a neutral result. All impacted absorbents were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite at the terminal prior to contractor demobilization. After departing off site, Clean Harbors personnel were asked to return to assist with the transfer of the contents of one (1) 85-gallon metal overpack drum to a one (1) 85-gallon poly drum due to the corrosive nature of the contained material. One (1) 85-gallon ploy drum was used to contain neutralizers and granular absorbents utilized during the transfer. Clean Harbors personnel staged one (1) 55-gallon poly drum, one (1) 85-gallon metal drum, and three (3) 85-gallon poly drums onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: On 1/13/2025 at approximately 1030, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 261690 at the ramp facility in Anchorage, reporting undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box, containing 10 inner boxes, and each of those contained 10 plastic bags containing safety matches.  The shipment was flagged and opened by the Customs division.  The Commercial Invoice identified the inner contents as "arithmetical bar"; however, Customs discovered a contradicting image in X-ray screening.  Upon making the discovery, Customs submitted the package to FedEx Dangerous Goods department for proper reporting.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations missing the required markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column169: BNSF personnel identified a potential release from the TILX 360231 while the car was in the Pasco Bowl Track 43.  The car was isolated pending inspection by BNSF Hazmat personnel.  Upon inspection, gasoline vapor was found emitting from the manway between the nozzle and hinged lid.  The manway was opened and found that the gasket was misaligned and not sealing completely.  The gasket was replaced with a nozzle gasket and the lid secured.  A new seal was installed and the car was released.  There were no identified ground impacts from the release and gasoline spilled on the car had evaporated.  Estimated release volume is based upon responder observations.
column170: The shipper should ensure that proper post loading inspections are conducted to include inspection of the manway gasket to ensure it is sufficient to contain the product while in transportation.(NAR:208)

On Saturday, January 4, 2025, a Occidental Chemical driver made a delivery of Hydrochloric Acid to the Occidental Chemical plant located in Hahnville, LA. The Occidental Chemical driver was loaded at an IMTT facility located in Geismar, LA. While the unloading process was underway, it was discovered that the bleeder valve on the product transfer line that goes to the product storage tank was left open. This resulted in approximately 2,500 gallons of Hydrochloric acid being released from the product line into the containment area. No injuries or exposure to chemical occurred as a result of this event, as well as no off-site impact or environmental impact. The offloading process was halted, bleeder valve closed, containment area drained to sump for processing, and remainder of offload was completed.
column170: The OxyChem truck driver immediately shut down the offloading operation upon discovery. The area was drained to a treatment sump, washed down and cleaned up. Occidental Chemical Taft Plant as well as Occidental Chemical Private Fleet has launched a joint investigation into this incident.

column169: Upon arrival at the destination terminal, this tote was discovered leaking inside the trailer. The tote was immediately turned on it's side to prevent further release. After investigation, it was determined that this tote was damaged due to a load shift during transit. An empty tote was used as dunnage to protect the tote and a piece of wood on the skid broke and was pushed into the tote, causing puncture. The material was a thick liquid and was contained to the trailer floor. The material was absorbed using absorbent material and placed into an overpack container for later disposal.
column170: It is hard to determine the exact cause of this incident because we do not know what the dunnage skid looked like before it was damaged and pushed into the tote. This incident may be used in future dock safety meetings to illustrate the importance of using solid, undamaged skids for dunnage to project freight during transport.

column169: On Sunday, January 5th, 2025, a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve appeared to be leaking from tank car # SHQX 70932 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Waterloo Yard Master who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car was set out to an isolation track (WA90) for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The contractor performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap. (The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight and the BOV handle was disengaged and pinned upon initial inspection). Also, the car seal provision indicator was not properly engaged according to the BOV diagram provided on the car. Cap was tightened and the BOV valve was inspected. The BOV valve handle was cycled exposing the valve was in the open position. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. The BOV cap gasket was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench. Upon tightening the BOV cap, CN emergency response contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV / Cap. Position

Operations Supervisor at 281 called Safety to report that a trailer arrived from 034 to 281 with a spill on it. The forklift operator that was about to unload the trailer advised that there was some cardboard covering a pallet of bags and when he moved the cardboard he discovered that at least one o f the bags was torn open and there was white powder all over. The operations supervisor advised that it looked like the bag was torn previously and someone had attempted to tape it over and cover it up. ~~Called CURA and spoke with Lizzie and advised we will need the crew to attempt to determine the  cause of the damage.~~Lizzie with CURA advised that the crew discovered two damaged 50 lb bags of UN3262 which released 3 lbs of powder to the trailer floor due to a forklift strike.

At 0920 on 1/9/25 HEPACO arrived onsite to the gasoline release. The gasoline that spilled impacted a 60' x 5' area on the asphalt parking lot. Oil dry is already placed down on the spill. On January 17th, 2025, at 12:34, a three-person Veolia team was conducting operations at the ASH Stevens customer site. The Veolia employees were in the process of loading totes onto a box truck using an electric pallet jack. The Veolia box truck was positioned at the customer's loading dock.  During the loading procedure, an incident occurred when a tote situated near the front of the box truck (one of the first to be loaded) was accidentally punctured. This happened as the pallet jack operator was attempting to place a second tote behind it, towards the rear/open end of the truck.  The puncture occurred in the left-hand lower quadrant of the 275-gallon tote. As a result, the contents began to leak, flowing from the front of the box truck towards the rear while it was still in the loading dock. The leaking material spilled off the truck and into the customer's secondary containment system, where it was successfully contained.  The customer's team promptly responded to the situation by transferring the remaining contents of the damaged tote into a new, undamaged container. They also managed to recover the spilled material from the secondary containment area. It is estimated that less than 250 gallons of the material was lost to the customer's containment system.
column170: 1. Veolia employees will be retrained on the use of the electric pallet jack.  2. The Veolia employee operating the pallet jack will be retrained with focus on hazard analysis in the operation of loading chemicals into box trucks. Consideration for the placement of "Forklift and Pallet Jack" forks - and how to place loaded cargo without damaging cargo to the fore of the truck.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding an industrial battery that fell over during the off-loading process leaking battery acid. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 20-gallon release onto the wooden dock floor in a 6’ x 8.5’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer in a 53’ x 10’ area. The contractor applied oil dry to the release and up-righted the dropped battery. The impacted absorbents, pallet pieces, and nylon cable were containerized into two 55-gallon DF’s for waste disposal. The battery was cleaned and re-palletized to ship onto the Consignee. XPO will manage all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: AN UNLOADER IN UNLOAD E DISCOVERED A FULLY LABELED HAZMAT PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. HE LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. WITHIN 3 MINUTES A DMP RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE CORRECT PPE WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. USING THE DECISION TREE AND CORRECT RESPONSE SHEET IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGE COULD BE SAFELY TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION IT WAS REVEALED THAT THE LID ON THE INNER 5 GALLON JERRICAN APPEARED TO BE MISSING A RUBBER GASKET AND THE LID WAS UNABLE TO MAKE A WATERTIGHT SEAL WHICH RESULTED IN 6 OUNCES OF LIQUID LEAKING OUT ONTO THE FIBERBOARD CARTON.

column169: On 01/06/2025 trailer 286454L arrived into BTR from MOB at 23:11 containing the 3 drum shipment on pro# 408307927. The trailer was set up for stripping at 23:30. On 01/07/2025 at 00:42, the shipment was moved& scanned to trailer 400195, located in door 25, by employee 53441. Approximately at 01:30 on 01/07/2025 trailer 400195 was being stripped for the Inbound operation. The employee stripping the trailer could smell the very strong odor of the chemical in the trailer. It was determined that one of the three drums had a fork hole in it& was Leaking. Safety was contacted& the proper channels were contacted from there. Louisiana State Police arrived on site& the in house clean up was performed. All items will be disposed of accordingly. After reviewing the cameras, considering the chemical is very thick& did not leave a trail. It was not determined if the order came into BTR Leaking. If the order was punctured during the initial off-loading of 286454L, or if the drum was punctured while off-loading 400195.

When facility was going to move around trailers to be loaded/unloaded it was noticed that material was dripping out the doors of the trailer around 1230 et. The put down absorbent to contain any runoff and begin absorbing the material. They opened the doors of the trailer to find that a drum had tipped over in transit. They then call for a team to come out and clean up the material that had release. The team arrived at 1445 et to review the information and began creating a plan. 1600 et the needed equipment and proper PPE needed arrived and the work began on the clean up. They uprighted the drum and began cleaning up any material that had released to the trailer and the pavement. The bung were checked and tightened and the absorbents that were used to clean up the material were placed into drums and disposed of properly. The clean up was completed at 2100 et.
column170: The cause of the release was due to pour load securement and the straping had fallen off the drums allowing the drum to tip over. The driver that picked up and transported the load is to complete retraining on load securement and proper inspections when picking up load and when dropping them.

On January 17, 2025, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1133 was crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) cups of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. The crew utilized cleaners, absorbents, and hand tools to remediate the site. The damaged pail and all impacted materials were containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums.

Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately two (2) quarts of material released from one (1) 1-gallon metal pails due to improperly loaded freight that resulted in the pails flipping over in the trailer and leaking. The released material impacted the trailer floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and gathered the spent material and damaged container and containerized it into two (2) 5-gallon poly drums. Three (3) 5-gallon poly drums were also used to contain three additional jugs of product due to contamination. A total of five (5) 5-gallon poly drums of waste were generated from this spill. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

During the screen process at the SWBA location a fiberboard box containing UN1266 was discovered. The outer fiberboard box did not have any DG markings or paperwork required for transit. The shipmnet is being held at the location.

XPO Logistics terminal BCH experienced a UN3082 Rhonox Herbicide release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 165-gallons of product released due to a forklift puncture. The entire trailer floor, a 150’ x 30’ area of the concrete lot below, and 4 drains and 1 catch basin were impacted. All drains lead to the catch basin where the material was contained. The crew utilized a vac truck to remove the product from the catch basin and drains leading to it. Absorbents were deployed to the trailer and concrete lot and worked in. Once the drains were done, absorbent boom was placed in them to collect any residual material. The product remaining the damaged tote was pumped out and the damaged tote was cut up and containerized. Crew returned to site and inspected the drains and flushed and vacuumed them out again. Additional wastewater was generated to be offloaded into totes. Samples were collected to confirm that no residual material remains in the catch basin and samples were collected from the nearby retention pond as well as a precaution. All wastewater was offloaded into totes and all solid cleanup debris was containerized into 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately fifteen (15) gallons of material released from one (1) 55-gallon metal drum due to improperly loading freight that resulted in the drum being punctured due to a forklift accident. The released material impacted the trailer floor and dock floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and gathered the spent material and containerized it into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: A third party driver was delivering drums to Veolia's 10-day intransit facility in Sauget, IL. As the driver was backing up, the trailer backed into a pallet of drums that were staged to be loaded onto a 10-day trailer. One of the drums was damaged by the underride bar on the back of the trailer, resulting in the drum to starting to leak. Approximately 10 gallons of waste flammable liquids was spilled onto an impervious surface. The spill was contained and cleaned up appropriately, and the damaged drum was overpacked for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column170: The third-party driver was unfamiliar with the site and the site's layout. In the future, a spotter will be used when trailers are backing up and there are staged containers in the area.

On 01/08/2025 hidden dangerous goods were discovered during the shipment inspection process at the DHL Express JFK Gateway located at the JFK International Airport, Cargo Building 263, Jamaica NY 11430. Transportation by road has been confirmed.

At ® proximately 06:57 hours for Flight 1755/SNU, ramp CSM notified the team of a passenger bag that was leaking. At the time, it was unclear whether the contents included a Dangerous Goods(DG) item. Customer HERNANDEZ/LEIDYS was identified as owner of the Leaking bag. Upon further investigation; it was disc6vered that passenger Hernandez had checked in early that morning at 03:41 hours for a later flight, FLT 1579/SNU, scheduled to depart at 12:40 hours. Despite this, her checked bag, tag#6001958417, was scanned and mistakenly loaded into Flight 1755 at 06:31 hours in the F2 compartment. A few minutes later, at 06:33 hour's, the FSC identified that the bag was Leaking and immediately removed it from the aircraft. Following the removal of the bag, Miami Fir6 Rescue and Environmental Coordinator Viviana Traverso were contacted to assess. Upon opening the bag, it was found to contain a broken gallon of muriatic acid, a can of primer paint, a used pool pump motor and other products. Some other bags were affected by contact with the acid but they had not been loaded on the aircraft.

AT THE UPS WORLDPORT FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY ONE AIR PACKAGE FROM SPAIN TO PERU WAS COVERED WITH BLACK SHRINK WRAPPING. THE BLACK COVERING WAS TORN DURING PACKAGE HANDLING REVEALING A CLASS 9 LITHIUM BATTERY DIAMOND LABEL ON AN INNER BOX. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION WE DISCOVERED THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED TWO INNER BOXES WITH CLASS 9 LITHIUM BATTERY DIAMOND LABELS, UN3091 LITHIUM METAL BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT AND EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER (001) 352-323-3500 THAT HAD BEEN COVERED. TWO CORUS EVO+ GAS VOLUME CONVERTER POWERED WITH LITHIUM METAL BATTERIES WERE CONTAINED IN THE BOXES. THE LITHIUM METAL BATTERIES ARE OVER 2 GRAMS OF EQUIVALENT LITHIUM METAL CONTENT. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THIS PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED FROM SPAIN USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER A24F24, HAM CRIOGENICA SL, 1 PROGRES C, ABRERA SPAIN 18630.

column169: A driver brought this package to QA's attention after picking it up at FedEx Office, 8057 WEDGEWOOD LN N, MAPLE GROVE, MN. Driver said the FXO employee explained strange situation that occurred with the customer dropping it off. The customer allegedly tried to offer it with Class 9 diamonds on it, but the FXO employee refused to accept, so the customer left and came back later with the Class 9 diamonds removed. FXO employee accepted it at that time but told driver about this. Driver told QA. The DG Nav specialist opened it for inspection and found that it contains a solar generator classified as UN3480. While there is a small UN3480 printed on the box, the customer seems to have deliberately removed the Class 9 diamonds to render it undeclared. Customer's return address is a business in Florida, but the last name connected to his first name in FAST when searching the business address appears fake. The phone number listed on the Fedex label is fake.
